Aghion & Tirole (1997): Model Setup
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Principal-agent framework: Agent is choosing among 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq3$
\end_inset

 a priori identical projects.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Project 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 has profit 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{k}$
\end_inset

 for the principal and private benefit 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{k}$
\end_inset

 for the agent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
They can also do nothing: 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{0}=b_{0}=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Congruence:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Choosing the principal's preferred project gives her 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 and the agent 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta b$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Choosing the agent's preferred project gives him 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 and the principal 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha B$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $0<\alpha,\beta\leq1$
\end_inset

 are exogenous parameters
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Aghion & Tirole (1997): Model Setup
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Principal is risk neutral.
 Utility is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B_{k}-w
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 is wage paid to the agent
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Agent is risk averse and has limited liability: 
\begin_inset Formula $w\geq0$
\end_inset

.
 Utility is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u\left(w\right)+b_{k}
\]

\end_inset

Agent is so risk averse that 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 can't depend on outcomes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Initially, nobody knows projects' payoffs.
 Gathering information is costly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If agent pays cost 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{A}\left(e\right)$
\end_inset

 he learns the payoffs of all projects with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

.
 With probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1-e$
\end_inset

 he learns nothing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Principal can pay cost 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{P}\left(E\right)$
\end_inset

 to learn payoffs with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

.
 With probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1-E$
\end_inset

 she learns nothing.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Aghion & Tirole (1997): Authority
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
P-formal authority:
\emph default
 The principal has formal authority.
 She may overrule the agent's recommendation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
A-formal authority: 
\emph default
The agent picks his preferred project and cannot be overruled by the principal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Contracts specify an allocation of formal authority to either the principal
 or the agent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Real authority:
\emph default
 Who actually gets to make the decision? Either because agent has formal
 authority or because P is just 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

rubber-stamping
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 agent's recommendation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Timing:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Prinicpal proposes a contract
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Parties gather information
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The party without formal authority communicates a subset of the projects'
 payoffs (s)he has learned
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The controlling party picks a project
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Aghion & Tirole (1997): Utilities
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Under 
\emph on
P-
\emph default
formal authority, the utilities are:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
u_{P} & =\underbrace{EB}_{\text{P picks her preferred project}}+\underbrace{\left(1-E\right)e\alpha B}_{\text{A suggests his preferred project}}-g_{P}\left(E\right)\\
u_{A} & =\underbrace{E\beta b}_{\text{P picks her preferred project}}+\underbrace{\left(1-E\right)eb}_{\text{A suggests his preferred project}}-g_{A}\left(e\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Under 
\emph on
A-
\emph default
formal authority, the utilities are:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
u_{P}^{d} & =\underbrace{e\alpha B}_{\text{A picks his preferred project}}+\underbrace{\left(1-e\right)EB}_{\text{P suggests her preferred project}}-g_{P}\left(E\right)\\
u_{A}^{d} & =\underbrace{eb}_{\text{A picks his preferred project}}+\underbrace{\left(1-e\right)E\beta b}_{\text{P suggests her preferred project}}-g_{A}\left(e\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Aghion & Tirole (1997): Basic Tradeoff
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
In this model there is a basic tradeoff between loss of control and initiative.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The reason is that efforts are 
\emph on
strategic substitutes: 
\emph default
The more effort the principal makes, the less the agent wants to (&vv).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
To see this, the FOCs for effort when the principal has formal authority
 are
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left(1-\alpha e\right)B & =g_{P}^{\prime}\left(E\right)\\
\left(1-E\right)b & =g_{A}^{\prime}\left(e\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Both of these reaction curves slope 
\emph on
down
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Imagine the principal's effort became more costly: 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{P}^{\prime}\uparrow$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Probability of learning the best project goes down.
 The principal loses real authority (control)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The reduction in 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 will encourage initiative by the agent:, 
\begin_inset Formula $e\uparrow$
\end_inset

.
 The principal gains
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Aghion & Tirole (1997): Delegation
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
If the principal cedes formal authority to the agent the effort FOCs become
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left(1-e\right)B & =g_{P}^{\prime}\left(E\right)\\
\left(1-\beta E\right)b & =g_{A}^{\prime}\left(e\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
These yield an equilibrium 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(E^{d},e^{d}\right)$
\end_inset

 where
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $e<e^{d}$
\end_inset

: Greater initiative by the agent
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $E>E^{d}$
\end_inset

: Loss of formal 
\emph on
and
\emph default
 real authority to the agent.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Less effort required from principal 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Agent is better off 
\begin_inset Formula $\rightarrow$
\end_inset

 slackens participation constraint so could lower wage
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Aghion & Tirole (1997): Span of Control
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Consider a principal with multiple agents where the principal doesn't want
 to delegate.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
How many agents to hire? How to encourage effort among many agents? 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 identical agents.
 Each one solving the problem above.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Principal's disutility is 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{P}\left(\sum_{i}E_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

, agents' tasks are independent.
 Fixed cost 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 per agent.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u_{P}=\sum_{i}\left[E_{i}B+\left(1-E_{i}\right)e_{i}\alpha B-f\right]-g_{P}\left(\sum_{i}E_{i}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Aghion & Tirole (1997): Span of Control
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Assume a symmetric equilibrium, each agent gets the same effort 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 from the principal.
 FOCs are
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left(1-\alpha e\right)B & =g_{P}^{\prime}\left(mE\right)\\
\left(1-E\right)b & =g_{A}^{\prime}\left(e\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

with solution 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ E\left(m\right),e\left(m\right)\right\} $
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Principal's utility from 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 agents is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u_{P}\left(m\right)\equiv mR\left(E\left(m\right),e\left(m\right)\right)-g_{P}\left(mE\left(m\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $R\left(E\left(m\right),e\left(m\right)\right)\equiv E\left(m\right)B+\left[1-E\left(m\right)\right]e\left(m\right)\alpha B-f$
\end_inset

 is revenue per agent.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Frame
\begin_inset Argument 4
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Aghion & Tirole (1997): Span of Control
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The optimal team size 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 then satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{du_{P}}{dm} & =\underbrace{\underbrace{R\left(E\left(m\right),e\left(m\right)\right)}_{\text{extra revenue}}-\underbrace{E\left(m\right)g_{P}^{\prime}\left(mE\left(m\right)\right)}_{\text{overload cost}}}_{\text{Marginal profit}<0}\\
 & \quad+\underbrace{m\frac{\partial R}{\partial e}\frac{\partial e}{\partial m}}_{\text{initiative effect }>0}=0
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Principal commits to overhiring, being overloaded and underinvesting in
 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 in order to encourage initiative 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
